			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Who are you, and why do you play in Molto Espressivo?<a name="56807"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 15 04 6:48 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><i>1. What was your EQ experience prior to joining Molto? </i>
<br />

<br />
I started EQ with the Velious expansion.  Klapton was my first toon, a Bard on Vazaelle server.  My playtime back then was much more limited than it is now, and I levelled slowly.  I did have lots of downtime at work, however, where I could hang out on the eqdiva message boards.  There I studied the art of barding outside the game to maximize the little bit of playtime I had.  I also became well known for providing helpful answers to newbie questions on the boards.
<br />

<br />
<i>2. Why did you join Molto? </i>
<br />

<br />
Orignally, my idea was simply to have SIX bards play together once a week, to see what a full group of Bards could do.  I had not idea at the time that it would be big enough to be a guild.  When we became a real guild, since iIt was my crazy idea, everyone made me be the leader of it too.  I didn't really have any desire (nor do I now) to be in CHARGE of anything.  So, you will notice that Molto has very few rules, and a very care-free atmosphere most of the time.
<br />

<br />
<i>3. What are your favorite memories of Molto? </i>
<br />

<br />
The first real &quot;Rolling Ball of Death&quot; was a run through the Warrens when we were somewhere around lvl 10.  It was insanely fun seeing all those Kobalds jumping all over and &quot;Wincing&quot; from six bards singing Chords of Dissoance, lol.
<br />

<br />
When we were all very young, and had next to no money at all, Stretto made a brave dash to Katta Castellum to get two Combine Drums and a Combine Lute.  That was all we could afford at the time, having pooled all our cash together.  I got the Lute, since I was the designated Instrument Twister of the group, hehe.
<br />

<br />
That night in Splitpaw was a BLAST.  Paw has always been one of my favorite zones, and I have the spawn memorized to this day.  It can be charm-pulled in pairs beautifully.  We learned many things in that dungeon, including the fact that 5 bards singing mez on a caster makes it pretty much impossible for them to cast... EVER, lol.  We were almost all still in our 20s, and well below the proper levels to be hunting in there,  (AND untwinked, mind you!), and we KICKED BUTT.
<br />

<br />
It was Vyvache that spotted that TDoK in bazaar that night.  It was actually within our reach, if we ALL gave what we had.  So we did.  We gave it to Ayuir, who was our highest level bard at that time.  She had been waiting patiently, working on AAs and tradeskills to pass her time while waiting for us to all level up.
<br />

<br />
Our first allbard LDoN mission was another memorable moment.  We have done many of them since, but I remember 5 of us doing a Mistmoore mission in our 50s, and kicking butt.  And we did NOT kite.  (We have successfully aggro-kited mobs in LDoNs as well).
<br />

<br />
<i>4. What is your typical day in Molto like? </i>
<br />

<br />
Well, I generally log on, say hi, and see what's happenning.  I also raid frequently with AWNN, so I usually see if they are keeling anything.  If anyone in the guild is doing and epic camp, I will almost always head straight there and help out.  
<br />

<br />
After checking what's up, I usually go LFG.  I used to solo a lot, but have grown tired of it over the years.  I love the interaction of group play best, of all the activities in EQ.  I like it better than raiding, better than soloing...  I especially love pulling and crowd controlling for groups.  Needless to say, I get frequent invites to pull for LDoN missions.  If it is a hard mission, I usually die a couple times, and whine a lot about how much my armor sucks.
<br />

<br />
<i>5. Any other comments you would have about your time in Molto are welcome.</i>
<br />

<br />
I have had a blast.  I feel very good about what Molto has become: something much larger than my original vision ever dreamed it would be.  This is the most generous, fun-loving bunch of people I have ever encountered in my EQ experience.  Thank you all for making my little dream a reality.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=564823">Scherzo Glissando </a><BR>
Maestro, Molto Espressivo</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
