			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Who are you, and why do you play in Molto Espressivo?<a name="59975"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 1 04 3:30 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>1) I started EQ 3 years ago, on Sept 1, 2001.  One of my sons had &quot;borrowed&quot; the account of a friend and was playing.  I was looking over his shoulder while he negotiated the tree city in Kelethin-- drunk.  I thought at the time that it was a very strange game.  He talked about wizards and clerics and good and evil.  My youngest was dying to play, so on a whim I bought the game, installed it on my computer at work and tried it (testing it out of course for it's appropriateness for young minds!)
<br />

<br />
My first character was a wizard.  I was so dumb that I put all my points into wisdom and immediately drowned my character in the lake in Felwithe, losing my newbie note.  I couldn't figure out how to get out of the water.  I was standing, bewildered and depressed when a very kind lady wizard saw me, and actually talked to me!  Even more surprising, she helped me, showed me the trainer, gave me money and clothes and directions!  I was so impressed that there was another human being playing the same game as me who was helpful and kind that I was instantly hooked.  I never forgot that lesson-- the people playing EQ are real.  Every single char has a human being behind it.
<br />

<br />
2) I was playing my 55 bard on Saryrn when I read about Molto Espressivo.  Also, one of my Guildies, Scat(who is now Raadil in Molto), had made a char on FV for the first all bard get together and he had related the antics of a group of bards who could not understand each other's language, had no weapons or gear, and were zerging the pit in Shar Val.  I was facinated at the prospect of learning the things I had only read about on eqdiva, so I made a bard and joined them the very next week.
<br />

<br />
3) Oh my favorite memories of Molto, gosh lets see...  Scherzo drowning in Oasis while Krescendo and I died laughing.  Errrr, Scherzo drowning in the pool in PoK, while afk training... Our first excursion into Split Paw, where Scherzo was practicing intimidation and it actually worked!  (We all died laughing!)  Trying to kill Misterioso on his first day in Molto by using him as an experimental subject as Scherzo and I tested songs on him in the arena.  Misterioso showing me the secrets of Norrath, the windmills in Steamfont (one of my favorite memories...) and the heights of Felwithe (a stunning view.)  Some of the greatest groups I have ever had-- fear kiting in LOIO, and I got to be the puller!  The memories are many and wonderful...
<br />

<br />
4) In the beginning, my day was: Log in and start hunting for bone chips and CB belts to level up new members.  I also spent many, many hours creating tarnished weapons and converting them into ore, selling the ore and buying backpacks and songs for the new members who joined daily.  Huge chunks of time were spent on language lessons for all.  Now I log on, say hi to everyone and get to work.  I talk to new bards, give out gear if I have it, invite new members, check the raid channel for upcoming events, solve guild problems (not many of those but they do pop up from time to time.)  I am an Officer, a Diplomat, a Mommy, a Teacher, a Translator and a Cheerleader.  I wear many hats in Molto.
<br />

<br />
5)  I love Molto.  I have watched it grow from the very beginning of its existence to now.  I have enjoyed every single minute of being a bard on FV.  I love my friends.  I thank Misterioso and Freedym for dying for me and for putting up with me in all my idiocy as I try to learn to be a better bard.  I thank you all for making Molto what it is-- the most unique experience in all of EQ!
<br />

<br />
Sonnatta
<br />
Concert Mistress
<br />
Molto Espressivo</span></td>
